label chapter7:

    # [Scene: Council Hall | Late Afternoon]

    scene bg ch7_453e40_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Urgent string ostinato, high tempo]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Rapid camera clicks, murmured approvals, the low hum of people leaning in]
    "You are standing where the chamber feels narrowest—shoulder-to-shoulder with Livia Chen, her trench coat immaculate at the collar, the fabric swallowing the studio lights. Behind her, investors lean forward like a pack sensing weather. In front"
    "of you, the council benches bloom into a small orchard of polished suits and blinking devices. The sea beyond the glass presses against the horizon, dark and indifferent."
    "The room exhales relief and the sound is almost obscene. Cameras flash. Someone claps, a short, startled bark that seeds the applause. For the first time in months you feel a practical tide: funding lines stamped, supply contracts nodding into being. The ledger world is opening up—concrete, measurable, immediate."
    "But your chest is a locked drum. The rhythm of it is too loud. You can feel your field notebook thick at your hip like a guilty thing."
    show livia_chen at left:
        zoom 0.7

    livia_chen "Measured scientific leadership—exactly what the town needed, Mara. You cut through theater.' (She slides a tablet across the lectern—slick glass, a wallpaper of deadline bars and red markers. The funding windows blink like small alarms.) 'This window doesn't wait. Three bids in ninety days. Milestones every quarter. Oversight committee to monitor compliance."
    "You touch the tablet because your fingers need the anchor of cold glass. The deadlines skitter across the screen: procurement, environmental assessments compressed into bureaucratic time, contractors pre-cleared. The fonts are clean; the risks are packaged"
    "in bullet points. Your stomach drops into the tone of someone who has measured too many probabilities and found one that will cost more than numbers can show."

    "Tess O'Malley, standing a few steps back with her fluorescent lanyard clutched like a talisman, leans in. Her eyes are wide, raw. Tess O'Malley" "Ms. Kestrel—will there be guarantees for the neighborhoods outside the plan? The—' (she swallows) '—the ones with the older foundations?"

    "Livia Chen gives the practiced smile that has saved more meetings than you can count. Livia Chen" "We will mitigate. There are buyout options. Transition assistance. Jobs. We will bring engineering to the table.' (Her voice smooths to assurance.) 'And with Mara’s recommendations integrated, this will be science-led and accountable."

    "Tess O'Malley’s shoulders twitch; the lanyard digs into her palm. Tess O'Malley" "That's not what people outside say. They're afraid—"

    livia_chen "Fear is understandable. But fear is not a plan.' (She looks at you, and the look is both a benediction and a billing statement.) 'We needed an expert to make the case, Mara. You did it. You gave them something they could fund."
    "You nod because your lungs have no better move. You can feel Elias 'Eli' Rowan watching you from the gallery—his grey-blue eyes narrowed, jaw set like a hinge. He looks like someone who has just walked"
    "into a dance where he doesn't know the steps and his palms smell of solvent. His paint-splattered jumpsuit reads like a defiant map of every late night he’s spent trying to fix things without burning them."
    "He stands an island of grit amid the varnished crowd."
    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan catches your eye. He doesn't rise to interrupt; he lets the noise of the room become the argument. You hold his look and say nothing. The silence between you is weather: sharp, charged, full of static."

    "Voice from the back" "You sold us out."
    "You taste metal. Your hands are not steady."

    "Livia Chen squeezes your arm in a way that should be comforting but feels like a contract signature. Livia Chen" "They'll see the jobs, the stabilization—give it time, Mara. The optics shift the moment the first pier goes up."
    "You try to answer and nothing you say will rearrange the room. Your training reaches for risk matrices and sensitivity analyses; it finds only the jagged edge of human consequence. The spreadsheet in your head begins to noisily enumerate who benefits and who is bumped—so many small, irreplaceable line items."

    menu:
        "Reassure Tess quietly":
            "You step toward Tess, voice hushed: 'We will insist on covenants—community seats on oversight. I'll push for them.' She nods once, fragile, and clings to the hope like a rope."
        "Turn to Elias 'Eli' Rowan and meet his gaze":
            "You catch Elias 'Eli' Rowan's eye and let a laugh that isn't funny escape you. He widens his brow, as if you have handed him a map with the wrong coordinates. His jaw hardens; he says nothing, but his silence tells you the shape of things to come."

    # --- merge ---
    "The choices make a small crack in the chamber. You chose words—attempts to patch—or you chose the honesty of a look. Both land imperfectly. The crowd moves on; the cameras barrel toward the next talking head. The administrative machinery begins to hum: contracts, NDAs, legal pads scrawled with clauses."
    hide livia_chen

    scene bg ch7_453e40_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Notification pings sync like a metronome — emails arriving, calendar invites, procurement notices]

    "You leave the hall under a soft rain of flash interviews and TV crews. Livia Chen walks a step ahead, radiating the kind of calm that is either certainty or practiced performance. Her brooch reflects back a jagged sun streak; the image of a wave is pretty and strategically placed. Her voice is lower now, only for you. Livia Chen" "We need your signatures on the oversight schedule tonight. We need the lab to begin baseline sampling tomorrow. Will you brief the engineers, Mara?"
    "The ask is precise. The hour is small. Your reply tastes like a resignation letter. You say yes."
    # [Scene Transition: Night falls over New Aster. The harbor lights look like small, tired moons.]
    # [Scene: Estuary Research Lab | Early Evening]

    scene bg ch7_453e40_3 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Percussive electronics driving faster]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The whir of centrifuges, the scratch of pens, the low chatter of engineers in motion]
    "You push through the lab door and the air changes—sterile, cool, the smell of disinfectant trying to sterilize consequence. A row of engineers gathers, sleeves rolled, machines pinging. On the counters: tidy stacks of proposals, risk matrices, CAD prints. The materials are cleanly laid out like soldiers in formation."

    "Lead Engineer (Kai)" "Ms. Kestrel, we ran the hydrodynamic model against the proposed wall configuration. Initial projections reduce overtopping by seventy percent at design storm thresholds. Construction phase—eighteen months. Maintenance schedule—quarterly. We've identified anchor points, prefabrication sites, and supply chains."
    "You listen and the words are efficient: a clinical litany of success metrics. Each statistic is a promise written in steel. But in the spaces between them your mind keeps drawing maps of households and shrines that will be moved or submerged—places for which there are no budget lines."

    "You ask" "And displacement? Secondary flooding? Where do the modeled impacts shift the risk?"

    "Kai taps the screen, fingers precise. Kai" "We optimized for the town's protected core. Peripheral zones show increased shear stress—some redistribution. We've flagged those for mitigation study. We can pilot armoring, tide-evac routes, or selective elevation."
    "Your breath catches. The engineers' language is a comfort in its clarity, and a knife in its inevitability. Every optimization has a byproduct; every displacement has coordinates."

    "A door opens and Dr. Naomi Park steps in, hair knotting the fluorescent air like a banner. Her presence tightens the room. Dr. Naomi Park" "Mara.' (She folds her arms, gaze hard.) 'I read the brief. Centralized infrastructure is clean on paper—but remember history. We concentrate protection, we push vulnerability to neighboring communities. We make winners and losers and then call it engineering."

    "You feel the lab constrict. Naomi's words are not abstract; they are a fossil record of past projects that gouged communities with the excuse of 'progress'. She moves through the group like a current, eyes catching yours. Dr. Naomi Park" "You know this, Mara. You know what we lose when we let the ledger weigh more than the people who live outside its margins."

    "You find your voice and it is small, urgent. You say" "What alternatives do we have that meet both the procurement demands and keep neighborhoods intact?"

    "Naomi's reply is direct and sharp" "Insistence. Legal covenants. Community representation on oversight—binding conditions. Phased builds with community-led pilots funded in parallel. But it requires time, transparency, and political will. It requires Livia to accept constraints she currently has incentives to avoid."
    "Her words hang like dampness. The lab feels suddenly like an interrogation room for ethics. You think of the tablet in the Council Hall, the red-marked funding windows, the culled deadlines. You feel yourself boxed in by every clock."

    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan steps in through the doorway—he had followed you, you realize, tracks of salt on his boots. He has the look of someone who has spent too many nights awake hoping the next fix will not fail. Elias 'Eli' Rowan" "They want to bolt down a single answer to a problem that's been creeping for decades. This wall—if it's the whole story—it's an eraser for the stories that don't make it into the blueprint."

    "Kai bristles. Kai" "Engineer to engineer—what you're proposing is operationally risky. Phased pilots mean fragmented funding and higher unit costs."

    "Elias 'Eli' Rowan" "Fragmented funding means more people stay put. More people keep their histories."
    "The argument ticks louder. You feel it like thunder building—small shocks. The lab's fluorescent hum increases in your ears. You can see the spreadsheets dancing like fireflies, each one a possible casualty."

    "Dr. Naomi Park moves closer, voice compressed. Dr. Naomi Park" "You already gave the endorsement, Mara. The seal is set in some ways. But it is not too late to thread protections in. Demand covenants. Make compliance conditional. Put community seats on the oversight board with veto rights for displacement. Insist on an independent social-impact audit before procurement."
    "Your hands go to your field notebook and you find the pages fluttering—tide charts, pressed seaweed, lists of stakeholders with little stars beside names you promised to protect. The pages look thin under the lab light."

    "Livia Chen's voice comes through your phone—text message previewed on the bench" "Press cycle tonight. Stakeholders pleased. Need your sign-off at 2300."

    menu:
        "Call Livia and demand community covenants now":
            "You dial. Livia answers on the second ring, tone clipped. 'We will consider language in oversight documents,' she says. Not a yes, not a no. The conversation ends with the sense you have requested a concession and received a polite deferral."
        "Draft a list of mandatory covenants to present tomorrow":
            "You pull a fresh page and begin to write: 'binding covenants; oversight seats; phased release of funds contingent on social audits.' Your hand is steadier. It's work by which you will measure later guilt."

    # --- merge ---
    "The lab's clock punctuates the moment. Any choice you make slides into policy and then into lived consequence. The arousal in you is a physical current—heartbeat quickening, palms slick, words spilling faster than you can frame them."
    "The truck outside finally moves, tires crunching on gravel. The campaign of construction begins in sound even as the paperwork continues on screens."

    "Naomi says, softer now" "Mara—if you do nothing now besides sign under pressure, you will not be wrong in the short term. You will be right in the ledger. But you'll have sacrificed the town's memory in exchange for scaffolding."
    "Livia's warmth—decisive, mobilizing—repeats itself in your mind. Her smile at the council, the clamp of investors' hands, the unblinking fonts of the tablet. The practical tide is real. The jobs are real. The protection is real."
    "So is the erasure."
    "You find yourself split like an old map torn down the middle. One edge is safety, measurable and immediate; the other is the grainy texture of porch lights and sagging signs, of people who will not be counted in quarterly reports. The tug is becoming a roar."
    "You press the pads of your fingers into your eyes until you see sparks. Your throat is raw. For the first time since this began, the scientist in you cannot inventory the variables into a comfortable"
    "certainty. The feeling is worse than doubt: it is grief with its face up close."

    scene bg ch7_453e40_4 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The whir of a centrifuge crescendoing into a high note]
    "You think of the boardwalk, weathered and half-submerged, of Grandma Hira humming by her doorway—of Elias 'Eli' Rowan, paint still under his nails, of Tess O'Malley’s lanyard squeezed white in her hand. The cost is not"
    "an abstract number. It is a litany of small, human things that do not pivot neatly into mitigation columns."
    "A text thread opens in your mind between the possible futures: the one in glossy press releases and the one people live. The currents pull both ways with equal force."
    "You look up at the ceiling lights, and for an instant everything is bright and too precise. The lab gives you answers that fit neat graphs. The town gives you questions that lick like salt at wounds."
    "You make a decision—small, internal, a tightening. You will go back and push. You will ask for covenants, for oversight, for a seat at the table that cannot be sold away by a budget line. But"
    "you already know—there will be consequences to pushing. There is always a threshold where insistence becomes obstruction; where the political calculus favours motion over deliberation."
    "The lab feels suddenly very loud. The truck outside finally moves, tires crunching on gravel. The campaign of construction begins in sound even as the paperwork continues on screens."
    "You breathe in, taste the disinfectant and something bitter underneath—salt and the tang of loss."
    "You close your field notebook slowly, the pages whispering shut like a small funeral."
    "You step out of the lab into the soft rain, the harbor lights smeared by wet glass. The town is a map of things that will be remade and things that will be left behind."
    "You are carrying both the anchor of what must be saved and the heavy keys of what you've set in motion."

    scene bg ch7_453e40_5 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Suspended chord resolves into a low, insistent pulse that demands movement]
    "You do not yet know whether the tide you summoned will lift the town whole—or wash away the parts that do not fit the blueprint."
    "You hold that not-knowing like a brand."

    scene bg ch7_453e40_6 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Fade Out]

    jump chapter8
    return
